!type: Basic Math
!deck: Math::Calculus::Limits
!tags: Math Calculus Limits Theory

!id: IHFp7aCyLb
!front: What is a continuous function?
!back:
A function \( f(x) \) is **continuous at a point** \( x = c \) if:

- \( f(c) \) exists: The function is defined at the point \( c \).
- \( \lim_{x \to c} f(x) \) exists: The limit of the function as \( x \) approaches \( c \) from both the left and right sides is the same.
- \( \lim_{x \to c} f(x) = f(c) \): The limit of the function as \( x \) approaches \( c \) is equal to the actual value of the function at \( c \).

If a function is continuous at every point in its domain, it is called a **continuous** function.
~~~

!id: m0iyqsxvib
!front: What do the one-sided limits \( \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \) and \( \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) \) mean, and how do they relate to the two-sided limit \( \lim_{x \to c} f(x) \)?
!back:
\( \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \) is the value \( f(x) \) approaches as \( x \) approaches \( c \) only through values less than \( c \); \( \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) \) is the analogous limit through values greater than \( c \).

The two-sided limit \( \lim_{x \to c} f(x) \) exists (as a finite number) if and only if both one-sided limits exist, are finite, and are equal to each other; its value is then their common value.
!extra: This equivalence is why one-sided limits are the natural tool for classifying discontinuities: whether they exist, are finite, and agree determines which kind of discontinuity occurs at \( c \).
~~~

!id: cxHfPbW878
!front: What makes a discontinuity at \( x = c \) **removable**?
!back:
Both one-sided limits exist, are finite, and agree:
\[ \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) = \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) = L, \]
but either \( f(c) \) is undefined or \( f(c) \neq L \).

It is called removable because defining (or redefining) \( f(c) = L \) makes \( f \) continuous at \( c \), without changing \( f \) anywhere else.
!extra: Example: \( f(x) = \frac{x^2-1}{x-1} \) at \( x=1 \); the limit is \( 2 \), but \( f(1) \) is undefined.
~~~

!id: FRG4k16Qle
!front: What makes a discontinuity at \( x = c \) a **jump discontinuity**?
!back:
Both one-sided limits exist and are finite, but they disagree:
\[ \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \neq \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x). \]
!extra: Unlike a removable discontinuity, no single choice of \( f(c) \) can make \( f \) continuous at \( c \) — the left and right values genuinely disagree.
~~~

!id: rDWoaDRK0w
!front: Why are removable and jump discontinuities both classified as **discontinuities of the first kind**?
!back:
Both share the requirement that \( \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \) and \( \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) \) each exist and are finite. They differ only in whether the two one-sided limits agree:

- equal one-sided limits, but \( f(c) \) undefined or wrong \(\to\) removable
- unequal one-sided limits \(\to\) jump
!related: Contrast with discontinuities of the second kind, where at least one one-sided limit fails to exist as a finite number.
~~~

!id: sYzobmQo2P
!front: What characterizes a discontinuity of the **second kind** (an **essential discontinuity**)?
!back: At least one of \( \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \) or \( \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) \) fails to exist as a finite number — either it does not exist at all, or it is infinite.
!extra: This is the complement of the first-kind case: first kind requires both one-sided limits to exist and be finite, so any failure of that condition puts the discontinuity in the second kind.
~~~

!id: KdFIcEaHYN
!front: Why is the discontinuity of \( f(x) = 1/x \) at \( x = 0 \) essential rather than removable?
!back: Because \( \lim_{x \to 0^-} f(x) = -\infty \) and \( \lim_{x \to 0^+} f(x) = +\infty \): neither one-sided limit is a finite number, so no value assigned to \( f(0) \) could make \( f \) continuous there.
!extra: This case is sometimes singled out as an **infinite discontinuity**, a special case of an essential discontinuity where the one-sided limit(s) are infinite rather than simply nonexistent.
~~~

!id: SUWcHWUEHj
!front: Give an example of an essential discontinuity caused by oscillation rather than by an infinite limit, and explain why.
!back: \( f(x) = \sin(1/x) \) at \( x = 0 \): as \( x \to 0 \), \( 1/x \) grows without bound, so \( \sin(1/x) \) oscillates through every value in \( [-1,1] \) infinitely often. Neither one-sided limit exists, since \( f(x) \) never settles near a single value.
!extra: This is called an **oscillating discontinuity**, a subtype of essential discontinuity.
~~~

!type: Basic Math (and reversed card)

!id: 68xkv0xO3S
!front: Notation for the **left-hand limit** of \( f \) at \( c \).
!back: \[ \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \]
~~~

!id: HzGPiTqpf7
!front: Notation for the **right-hand limit** of \( f \) at \( c \).
!back: \[ \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) \]
~~~

!type: Basic Math

!id: 5AD8AdtaEL
!front: What do the shorthand notations \( f(c^-) \) and \( f(c^+) \) mean, as used when discussing discontinuities?
!back:
They abbreviate the one-sided limits:
\[
\begin{align*}
    f(c^-) &:= \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) \\
    f(c^+) &:= \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x)
\end{align*}
\]
!extra: This is common shorthand in analysis. It is not evaluating \( f \) at some point called "\( c^- \)" — \( c^- \) is not itself an argument of \( f \).
~~~

!id: xqggw15jOh
!front: Why does differentiability at \( c \) imply continuity at \( c \)?
!back:
For \( x \neq c \) near \( c \),
\[ f(x) - f(c) = \frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c} \cdot (x-c). \]
If \( f'(c) \) exists, taking \( x \to c \) gives
\[ \lim_{x \to c} \big(f(x)-f(c)\big) = f'(c) \cdot 0 = 0, \]
so \( \lim_{x \to c} f(x) = f(c) \), which is exactly continuity at \( c \).
~~~

!id: fsU0X5W0dG
!front: Construct a counterexample showing continuity at a point does not imply differentiability there.
!back:
\( f(x) = |x| \) at \( c = 0 \): it is continuous since \( \lim_{x \to 0} |x| = 0 = f(0) \). But
\[ \lim_{h \to 0^-} \frac{|h|-0}{h} = -1, \qquad \lim_{h \to 0^+} \frac{|h|-0}{h} = 1, \]
so the one-sided derivatives disagree and \( f'(0) \) does not exist.
!related: The disagreement here is exactly analogous to a jump discontinuity in the one-sided *limits* of \( f \) itself — here it is the one-sided limits of the difference quotient that disagree instead.
~~~

!id: GGfqqaxYMg
!front: What does it mean for \( f \) to be **continuous from the right** (resp. **from the left**) at \( c \)?
!back: \( f \) is continuous from the right at \( c \) if \( f(c) \) exists and \( \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) = f(c) \). Continuous from the left is the same statement with \( \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) = f(c) \).
!extra: Two-sided continuity at \( c \) is equivalent to being continuous from both the left and the right at \( c \).
~~~

!id: fzHFwExGKp
!front: Why is continuity of \( f \) on a closed interval \( [a,b] \) stated using one-sided continuity at the endpoints \( a \) and \( b \)?
!back: Outside \( [a,b] \), \( f \) is not defined, so a genuine two-sided limit at \( a \) or \( b \) cannot be formed. All that can be asked is that \( f \) behave well from the side that lies in the domain: continuous from the right at \( a \), and continuous from the left at \( b \).
!extra: This is precisely the hypothesis theorems like the IVT and EVT need at the endpoints of \( [a,b] \).
~~~

!id: gSjP18zHWY
!front: What condition must hold at a boundary point \( c \) for a piecewise-defined function to be continuous there?
!back:
The left-hand limit (computed from the piece defined for \( x<c \)), the right-hand limit (from the piece for \( x>c \)), and \( f(c) \) itself must all agree:
\[ \lim_{x \to c^-} f(x) = \lim_{x \to c^+} f(x) = f(c). \]
!extra: It is not enough for the two pieces' formulas to agree in value at \( c \) if one of them is not itself continuous up to the boundary — the limiting behavior, not just the plugged-in value, is what must match.
~~~

!id: HafZTETOS6
!front: State the \( \varepsilon \)-\( \delta \) definition of continuity of \( f \) at \( c \).
!back:
\( f \) is continuous at \( c \) if for every \( \varepsilon>0 \) there exists \( \delta>0 \) such that for all \( x \) in the domain of \( f \),
\[ |x-c|<\delta \implies |f(x)-f(c)|<\varepsilon. \]
~~~

!id: 2311aqAnmI
!front: How does the \( \varepsilon \)-\( \delta \) definition of continuity relate to the limit-based definition (\( f(c) \) exists, \( \lim_{x\to c} f(x) \) exists, and equals \( f(c) \))?
!back: They are the same statement at different levels of precision. The limit-based definition names the ingredients: \( f(c) \) must exist, the limit must exist, and the two must agree. The \( \varepsilon \)-\( \delta \) definition is what "\( \lim_{x\to c} f(x) = f(c) \)" precisely means: however small a tolerance \( \varepsilon \) is demanded on the output, some tolerance \( \delta \) on the input suffices to guarantee it.
~~~

!id: UAn7ziYq3m
!front: Construct a counterexample showing the IVT's conclusion can fail if \( f \) is not continuous on \( [a,b] \).
!back: Let \( f(x) = -1 \) for \( x \in [a,m) \) and \( f(x) = 1 \) for \( x \in [m,b] \), for some \( m \in (a,b) \). Then \( f(a)=-1 \) and \( f(b)=1 \), so \( 0 \) lies between them, but \( f \) never takes the value \( 0 \) anywhere on \( [a,b] \). The jump discontinuity at \( m \) lets \( f \) skip over \( 0 \) entirely.
!related: Compare with the Intermediate Value Theorem card in `03-differentiation.note`, which requires continuity on \( [a,b] \) as a hypothesis.
~~~

!id: jBHWk5ISDd
!front: Construct a counterexample showing the EVT's conclusion can fail if \( f \) is not continuous on \( [a,b] \).
!back: Let \( f(x) = x \) for \( x \in [0,1) \) and \( f(1) = 0 \), on the closed bounded interval \( [0,1] \). Values of \( f(x) \) get arbitrarily close to \( 1 \) as \( x \to 1^- \), but \( f \) never equals \( 1 \) since \( f(1)=0 \); so \( f \) has no maximum on \( [0,1] \), even though the interval is closed and bounded.
!related: Compare with the Extreme Value Theorem, which requires continuity on \( [a,b] \) as a hypothesis.
~~~

!id: 829UsGT0NU
!front: Define the Dirichlet function and explain why it is discontinuous at every real number.
!back:
\[
    D(x) =
    \begin{cases}
        1 & x \in \mathbb{Q} \\
        0 & x \notin \mathbb{Q}
    \end{cases}
\]
Both the rationals and the irrationals are dense in \( \mathbb{R} \), so every neighborhood of any point \( c \) contains points where \( D=1 \) and points where \( D=0 \). Hence \( \lim_{x \to c} D(x) \) does not exist at any \( c \), and \( D \) is discontinuous everywhere.
~~~

!id: kYGWrBQkqs
!front: What is significant about the Weierstrass function, and why is it beyond the reach of elementary calculus to fully justify?
!back: The Weierstrass function is continuous at every real number but differentiable at none of them — a classical theorem, stated here without proof. It shows that continuity, even everywhere, does not imply any local smoothness: unlike \( |x| \), which fails to be differentiable at just one point, this function has no well-defined tangent direction anywhere.
!extra: Its standard proof relies on tools beyond elementary calculus, such as uniform convergence of an infinite series of cosine terms.
~~~
